1. delete() (on object OR condition)
✔ Case 1: delete object
$product = Product::find(1);
$product->delete();
👉 Meaning:
You already fetched the record
Then you delete it

Case 2: delete with condition
Product::where('price', '<', 10)->delete();
👉 Meaning:
delete many records using condition

2. destroy() (by ID only)
Product::destroy(1);
Product::destroy([1, 2, 3]);
👉 Meaning:
delete directly using PRIMARY KEY
no need to fetch object



Feature	                  delete()	          destroy()
Works on object            ✅	                  ❌
Works on condition	       ✅	                  ❌
Works with ID directly	   ❌                  	✅
Multiple IDs	             ❌                 	✅
Needs model instance	sometimes	no



  If you see:
$product->delete() → object delete
